# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: openid-connect
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] An **authentication protocol** is a type of computer communications protocol or cryptographic protocol specifically designed for transfer of authentication data between two entities.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] It allows the receiving entity to authenticate the connecting entity (e.g.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] Client connecting to a Server) as well as authenticate itself to the connecting entity (Server to a client) by declaring the type of information needed for authentication as well as syntax.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] It is the most important layer of protection needed for secure communication within computer networks.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] With the increasing amount of trustworthy information being accessible over the network, the need for keeping unauthorized persons from access to this data emerged.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] It is possible to steal one's identity in the computing world - special verification methods were invented to find out whether the person/computer requesting data is really who they say they are.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] The task of the authentication protocol is to specify the exact series of steps needed for execution of the authentication.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] All the included parties have to follow the protocol.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] A protocol has to be unambiguous - each step must be defined precisely.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] A protocol must be complete - must include a specified action for every possible situation.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] Alice (an entity wishing to be verified) and Bob (an entity verifying Alice's identity) are both aware of the protocol they agreed on using.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] Bob has Alice's password stored in a database for comparison.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] Bob checks the received password against the one stored in his database.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] Then he sends a packet saying "Authentication successful" or "Authentication failed" based on the result.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] This is an example of a very basic authentication protocol vulnerable to many threats such as eavesdropping, replay attack, man-in-the-middle attacks, dictionary attacks or brute-force attacks.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] Most authentication protocols are more complicated in order to be resilient against these attacks.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] Protocols are used mainly by Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP) servers to validate the identity of remote clients before granting them access to server data.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] Most of them use a password as the cornerstone of the authentication.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] In most cases, the password has to be shared between the communicating entities in advance.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] Password Authentication Protocol is one of the oldest authentication protocols.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] Authentication is initialized by the client sending a packet with credentials (username and password) at the beginning of the connection, with the client repeating the authentication request until acknowledgement is received.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] It is highly insecure because credentials are sent "in the clear" and repeatedly, making it vulnerable even to the most simple attacks like eavesdropping and man-in-the-middle based attacks.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] Although widely supported, it is specified that if an implementation offers a stronger authentication method, that method *must* be offered before PAP.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] Mixed authentication (e.g. the same client alternately using both PAP and CHAP) is also not expected, as the CHAP authentication would be compromised by PAP sending the password in plain-text.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] The authentication process in this protocol is always initiated by the server/host and can be performed anytime during the session, even repeatedly.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] The server sends a random string (usually 128B long).
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] The client uses the password and the string received as input to a hash function and then sends the result together with username in plain text.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] The server uses the username to apply the same function and compares the calculated and received hash.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] An authentication is successful when the calculated and received hashes match.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] EAP was originally developed for PPP(Point-to-Point Protocol) but today is widely used in IEEE 802.3, IEEE 802.11(WiFi) or IEEE 802.16 as a part of IEEE 802.1x authentication framework.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] The latest version is standardized in RFC 5247.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] The advantage of EAP is that it is only a general authentication framework for client-server authentication - the specific way of authentication is defined in its many versions called EAP-methods.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] Complex protocols used in larger networks for verifying the user (Authentication), controlling access to server data (Authorization) and monitoring network resources and information needed for billing of services (Accounting).
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] The oldest AAA protocol using IP based authentication without any encryption (usernames and passwords were transported as plain text).
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] Later version XTACACS (Extended TACACS) added authorization and accounting.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] Both of these protocols were later replaced by TACACS+.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] TACACS+ separates the AAA components thus they can be segregated and handled on separate servers (It can even use another protocol for e.g.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] It uses TCP (Transmission Control Protocol) for transport and encrypts the whole packet.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] Remote Authentication Dial-In User Service (RADIUS) is a full AAA protocol commonly used by Internet service providers.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] Credentials are mostly username-password combination based, and it uses NAS and UDP protocol for transport.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] Diameter (protocol) evolved from RADIUS and involves many improvements such as usage of more reliable TCP or SCTP transport protocol and higher security thanks to TLS.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] Kerberos is a centralized network authentication system developed at MIT and available as a free implementation from MIT but also in many commercial products.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] It is the default authentication method in Windows 2000 and later.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] The authentication process itself is much more complicated than in the previous protocols - Kerberos uses symmetric key cryptography, requires a trusted third party and can use public-key cryptography during certain phases of authentication if need be.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] Recent research in authentication protocols highlights advancements aimed at securing resource-constrained environments such as the Industrial Internet of Things (IoT).
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] These modern protocols employ advanced cryptographic techniques, including Elliptic Curve Cryptography (ECC), to enable secure mutual authentication and session key agreement while minimizing computational and energy overhead.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] Privacy-preserving mechanisms have also been integrated with biometric authentication to enhance security without compromising user confidentiality.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] Further emphasis has been placed on resistance to side-channel and replay attacks, alongside the achievement of forward and backward secrecy to protect session keys in dynamic network scenarios.
[src:openid-connect/authentication-protocol] These emerging technologies mark significant progress in making authentication more efficient and secure across evolving digital landscapes.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] A **federated identity** in information technology is the means of linking a person's electronic identity and attributes, stored across multiple distinct identity management systems.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] Federated identity is related to single sign-on (SSO), in which a user's single authentication ticket, or token, is trusted across multiple IT systems or even organizations.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] SSO is a subset of federated identity management, as it relates only to authentication and is understood on the level of technical interoperability, and it would not be possible without some sort of federation.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] In information technology (IT), federated identity management (FIdM) amounts to having a common set of policies, practices and protocols in place to manage the identity and trust into IT users and devices across organizations.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] Single sign-on (SSO) systems allow a single user authentication process across multiple IT systems or even organizations.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] SSO is a subset of federated identity management, as it relates only to authentication and technical interoperability.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] Centralized identity management solutions were created to help deal with user and data security where the user and the systems they accessed were within the same network – or at least the same "domain of control".
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] Increasingly, however, users are accessing external systems which are fundamentally outside their domain of control, and external users are accessing internal systems.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] The increasingly common separation of the user from the systems requiring access is an inevitable by-product of the decentralization brought about by the integration of the Internet into every aspect of both personal and business life.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] Evolving identity management challenges, and especially the challenges associated with cross-company, cross-domain access, have given rise to a new approach to identity management, known now as "federated identity management".
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] FIdM, or the "federation" of identity, describes the technologies, standards and use-cases which serve to enable the portability of identity information across otherwise autonomous security domains.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] The ultimate goal of identity federation is to enable users of one domain to securely access data or systems of another domain seamlessly, and without the need for completely redundant user administration.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] Identity federation comes in many flavors, including "user-controlled" or "user-centric" scenarios, as well as enterprise-controlled or business-to-business scenarios.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] Federation is enabled through the use of open industry standards and/or openly published specifications, such that multiple parties can achieve interoperability for common use-cases.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] Typical use-cases involve things such as cross-domain, web-based single sign-on, cross-domain user account provisioning, cross-domain entitlement management and cross-domain user attribute exchange.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] Use of identity federation standards can reduce cost by eliminating the need to scale one-off or proprietary solutions.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] It can increase security and lower risk by enabling an organization to identify and authenticate a user once, and then use that identity information across multiple systems, including external partner websites.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] It can improve privacy compliance by allowing the user to control what information is shared, or by limiting the amount of information shared.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] And lastly, it can drastically improve the end-user experience by eliminating the need for new account registration through automatic "federated provisioning" or the need to redundantly login through cross-domain single sign-on.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] The notion of identity federation is extremely broad, and also evolving.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] It could involve user-to-user and user-to-application as well as application-to-application use-case scenarios at both the browser tier and the web services or service-oriented architecture (SOA) tier.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] It can involve high-trust, high-security scenarios as well as low-trust, low-security scenarios.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] The levels of identity assurance that may be required for a given scenario are also being standardized through a common and open Identity Assurance Framework.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] It can involve user-centric use-cases, as well as enterprise-centric use-cases.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] The term "identity federation" is by design a generic term, and is not bound to any one specific protocol, technology, implementation or company.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] Identity federations may be bi-lateral relationships or multilateral relationships.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] In the latter case, the multilateral federation frequently occurs in a vertical market, such as in law enforcement (such as the National Identity Exchange Federation - NIEF), and research and education (such as InCommon).
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] If the identity federation is bilateral, the two parties can exchange the necessary metadata (assertion signing keys, etc.) to implement the relationship.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] In a multilateral federation, the metadata exchange among participants is a more complex issue.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] It can be handled in a hub-and-spoke exchange or by the distribution of a metadata aggregate by a federated operator.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] One thing that is consistent, however, is the fact that "federation" describes methods of identity portability which are achieved in an open, often standards-based manner – meaning anyone adhering to the open specification or standard can achieve the full spectrum of use-cases and interoperability.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] Identity federation can be accomplished any number of ways, some of which involve the use of formal Internet standards, such as the OASIS Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) specification, and some of which may involve open-source technologies and/or other openly published specifications (e.g.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] Information Cards, OpenID, the Higgins trust framework or Novell's Bandit project).
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] Technologies used for federated identity include SAML (Security Assertion Markup Language), OAuth, OpenID, Security Tokens (Simple Web Tokens, JSON Web Tokens, and SAML assertions), Web Service Specifications, and Windows Identity Foundation.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] The Federal Risk and Authorization Management Program (FedRAMP) is a government-wide program that provides a standardized approach to security assessment, authorization, and continuous monitoring for cloud products and services.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] The FedRAMP program supports the transition of federal agencies from legacy IT infrastructure to cloud-based computing environments.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] Here is a list of services that provide social login features which they encourage other websites to use.
[src:openid-connect/federated-identity] Related are federated identity login providers.
[src:openid-connect/identity-provider] An **identity provider** (abbreviated **IdP**, **IDP**, or **idp**) is a system entity that creates, maintains, and manages identity information for principals and also provides authentication services to relying applications within a federation or distributed network.
[src:openid-connect/identity-provider] Identity providers offer user authentication as a service.
[src:openid-connect/identity-provider] Relying party applications, such as web applications, outsource the user authentication step to a trusted identity provider.
[src:openid-connect/identity-provider] Such a relying party application is said to be *federated*, that is, it consumes federated identity.
[src:openid-connect/identity-provider] An identity provider is “a trusted provider that lets you use single sign-on (SSO) to access other websites.” SSO enhances usability by reducing password fatigue.
[src:openid-connect/identity-provider] It also provides better security by decreasing the potential attack surface.
[src:openid-connect/identity-provider] Identity providers can facilitate connections between cloud computing resources and users, thus decreasing the need for users to re-authenticate when using mobile and roaming applications.
[src:openid-connect/identity-provider] OpenID Connect (OIDC) is an identity layer on top of OAuth.
[src:openid-connect/identity-provider] In the domain model associated with OIDC, an identity provider is a special type of OAuth 2.0 authorization server.
[src:openid-connect/identity-provider] Specifically, a system entity called an OpenID Provider issues JSON-formatted identity tokens to OIDC relying parties via a RESTful HTTP API.
[src:openid-connect/identity-provider] The Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) is a set of profiles for exchanging authentication and authorization data across security domains.
[src:openid-connect/identity-provider] In the SAML domain model, an identity provider is a special type of authentication authority.
[src:openid-connect/identity-provider] Specifically, a SAML identity provider is a system entity that issues authentication assertions in conjunction with an SSO profile of SAML.
[src:openid-connect/identity-provider] A relying party that consumes these authentication assertions is called a SAML service provider.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Generally, the OAuth protocol provides a way for resource owners to provide a client application with secure delegated access to server resources.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] It specifies a process for resource owners to authorize third-party access to their server resources without providing credentials.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Designed specifically to work with Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP), OAuth essentially allows access tokens to be issued to third-party clients by an authorization server, with the approval of the resource owner.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] The third party then uses the access token to access the protected resources hosted by the resource server.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] OAuth began in November 2006 when Blaine Cook was developing an OpenID implementation for Twitter.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Meanwhile, Ma.gnolia needed a solution to allow its members with OpenIDs to authorize Mac OS X Dashboard widgets to access their service.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Cook, Chris Messina and Larry Halff from Magnolia met with David Recordon to discuss using OpenID with the Twitter and Magnolia APIs to delegate authentication.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] They concluded that there were no open standards for API access delegation.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] The OAuth discussion group was created in April 2007, for a small group of implementers to write the draft proposal for an open protocol.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] DeWitt Clinton from Google learned of the OAuth project, and expressed his interest in supporting the effort.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] In July 2007, the team drafted an initial specification.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Eran Hammer joined and coordinated the many OAuth contributions creating a more formal specification.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] On 3 October 2007, the OAuth Core 1.0 final draft was released.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] At the 73rd Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) meeting in Minneapolis in November 2008, an OAuth BoF was held to discuss bringing the protocol into the IETF for further standardization work.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] The event was well attended and there was wide support for formally chartering an OAuth working group within the IETF.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] The OAuth 1.0 protocol was published as RFC 5849, an informational Request for Comments, in April 2010.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Since 31 August 2010, all third party Twitter applications have been required to use OAuth.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] The OAuth 2.0 framework was published considering additional use cases and extensibility requirements gathered from the wider IETF community.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Albeit being built on the OAuth 1.0 deployment experience, OAuth 2.0 is not backwards compatible with OAuth 1.0.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] OAuth 2.0 was published as RFC 6749 and the Bearer Token Usage specification as RFC 6750, both standards track Requests for Comments, in October 2012.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] As of November 2024, the OAuth 2.1 Authorization Framework draft is a work in progress.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] It consolidates the functionality in RFCs OAuth 2.0, OAuth 2.0 for Native Apps, Proof Key for Code Exchange, OAuth 2.0 for Browser-Based Apps, OAuth Security Best Current, and Bearer Token Usage.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] On 23 April 2009, a session fixation security flaw in the 1.0 protocol was announced.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] It affects the OAuth authorization flow (also known as "3-legged OAuth") in OAuth Core 1.0 Section 6.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Version 1.0a of the OAuth Core protocol was issued to address this issue.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] In January 2013, the Internet Engineering Task Force published a threat model for OAuth 2.0.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Among the threats outlined is one called "Open Redirector"; in early 2014, a variant of this was described under the name "Covert Redirect" by Wang Jing.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] OAuth 2.0 has been analyzed using formal web protocol analysis.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] This analysis revealed that in setups with multiple authorization servers, one of which is behaving maliciously, clients can become confused about the authorization server to use and may forward secrets to the malicious authorization server (AS Mix-Up Attack).
[src:openid-connect/oauth] This prompted the creation of a new best current practice internet draft that sets out to define a new security standard for OAuth 2.0.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Assuming a fix against the AS Mix-Up Attack in place, the security of OAuth 2.0 has been proven under strong attacker models using formal analysis.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] One implementation of OAuth 2.0 with numerous security flaws has been exposed.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] In April and May 2017, about one million users of Gmail (less than 0.1% of users as of May 2017) were targeted by an OAuth-based phishing attack, receiving an email purporting to be from a colleague, employer or friend wanting to share a document on Google Docs.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Those who clicked on the link within the email were directed to sign in and allow a potentially malicious third-party program called "Google Apps" to access their "email account, contacts and online documents".
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Within "approximately one hour", the phishing attack was stopped by Google, who advised those who had given "Google Apps" access to their email to revoke such access and change their passwords.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] In the draft of OAuth 2.1 the use of the PKCE (RFC 7636) extension for native apps has been recommended to all kinds of OAuth clients, including web applications and other confidential clients in order to prevent malicious browser extensions from performing OAuth 2.0 code injection attacks.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] OAuth framework specifies several grant types for different use cases.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Facebook's Graph API only supports OAuth 2.0.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Google supports OAuth 2.0 as the recommended authorization mechanism for all of its APIs.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Microsoft also supports OAuth 2.0 for various APIs and its Azure Active Directory service, which is used to secure many Microsoft and third party APIs.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] OAuth can be used as an authorizing mechanism to access secured RSS/Atom feeds.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Access to RSS/ATOM feeds that require authentication has always been an issue.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] For example, an RSS feed from a secured Google Site could not have been accessed using Google Reader.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Instead, three-legged OAuth would have been used to authorize that RSS client to access the feed from the Google Site.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Free software client implementations of the OAuth2 protocol such as the LibreOffice OAuth2OOo extension allows access to remote resources (ie: via the Google API or the Microsoft Graph API and OAuth 2.0) and possibly even with the LibreOffice Basic language.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] This makes it very easy to write and use HTTP requests supporting the OAuth 2.0 protocol in LibreOffice macros.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] OAuth is a service that is complementary to and distinct from OpenID.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] OAuth is unrelated to OATH, which is a reference architecture for authentication, not a standard for authorization.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] However, OAuth is directly related to OpenID Connect (OIDC), since OIDC is an authentication layer built on top of OAuth 2.0.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] OAuth is also unrelated to XACML, which is an authorization policy standard.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] OAuth can be used in conjunction with XACML, where OAuth is used for ownership consent and access delegation whereas XACML is used to define the authorization policies (e.g., managers can view documents in their region).
[src:openid-connect/oauth] OAuth is an *authorization* protocol, rather than an *authentication* protocol.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Using OAuth on its own as an authentication method may be referred to as pseudo-authentication.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] The following diagrams highlight the differences between using OpenID (specifically designed as an authentication protocol) and OAuth for authorization.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] The site sees that the user is not authenticated.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] It formulates a request for the identity provider, encodes it, and sends it to the user as part of a redirect URL.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Once the identity provider is satisfied that the user is sufficiently authenticated, it processes the application's request, formulates a response, and sends that back to the user along with a redirect URL back to the application.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] The application decodes the identity provider's response, and carries on accordingly.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] (OAuth only) The response includes an access token which the application can use to gain direct access to the identity provider's services on the user's behalf.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] The access token acts as a kind of "valet key" that the application can include with its requests to the identity provider, which prove that it has permission from the user to access those APIs.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Because the identity provider typically (but not always) authenticates the user as part of the process of granting an OAuth access token, it is tempting to view a successful OAuth access token request as an authentication method itself.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] However, because OAuth was not designed with this use case in mind, making this assumption can lead to major security flaws.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] XACML is a policy-based, attribute-based access control authorization framework.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] XACML and OAuth can be combined to deliver a more comprehensive approach to authorization.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] OAuth does not provide a policy language with which to define access control policies.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] XACML can be used for its policy language.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Where OAuth focuses on delegated access (I, the user, grant Twitter access to my Facebook wall), and identity-centric authorization, XACML takes an attribute-based approach which can consider attributes of the user, the action, the resource, and the context (who, what, where, when, how).
[src:openid-connect/oauth] XACML provides more fine-grained access control than OAuth does.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] OAuth is limited in granularity to the coarse functionality (the scopes) exposed by the target service.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] As a result, it often makes sense to combine OAuth and XACML together where OAuth will provide the delegated access use case and consent management and XACML will provide the authorization policies that work on the applications, processes, and data.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Lastly, XACML can work transparently across multiple stacks (APIs, web SSO, ESBs, home-grown apps, databases...).
[src:openid-connect/oauth] OAuth focuses exclusively on HTTP-based apps.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Eran Hammer resigned from his role of lead author for the OAuth 2.0 project, withdrew from the IETF working group, and removed his name from the specification in July 2012.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Hammer cited a conflict between web and enterprise cultures as his reason for leaving, noting that IETF is a community that is "all about enterprise use cases" and "not capable of simple".
[src:openid-connect/oauth] "What is now offered is a blueprint for an authorization protocol", he noted, "that is the enterprise way", providing a "whole new frontier to sell consulting services and integration solutions".
[src:openid-connect/oauth] In comparing OAuth 2.0 with OAuth 1.0, Hammer points out that it has become "more complex, less interoperable, less useful, more incomplete, and most importantly, less secure".
[src:openid-connect/oauth] He explains how architectural changes for 2.0 unbound tokens from clients, removed all signatures and cryptography at a protocol level and added expiring tokens (because tokens could not be revoked) while complicating the processing of authorization.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] David Recordon later also removed his name from the specifications for unspecified reasons.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] Dick Hardt took over the editor role, and the framework was published in October 2012.
[src:openid-connect/oauth] David Harris, author of the email client Pegasus Mail, has criticised OAuth 2.0 as "an absolute dog's breakfast", requiring developers to write custom modules specific to each service (Gmail, Microsoft Mail services, etc.), and to register specifically with them.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The OpenID standard provides a framework for the communication that must take place between the identity provider and the OpenID acceptor (the "relying party").
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] An extension to the standard (the OpenID Attribute Exchange) facilitates the transfer of user attributes, such as name and gender, from the OpenID identity provider to the relying party (each relying party may request a different set of attributes, depending on its requirements).
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The OpenID protocol does not rely on a central authority to authenticate a user's identity.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Moreover, neither services nor the OpenID standard may mandate a specific means by which to authenticate users, allowing for approaches ranging from the common (such as passwords) to the novel (such as smart cards or biometrics).
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The final version of OpenID is OpenID 2.0, finalized and published in December 2007.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The term *OpenID* may also refer to an identifier as specified in the OpenID standard; these identifiers take the form of a unique Uniform Resource Identifier (URI), and are managed by some "OpenID provider" that handles authentication.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Facebook did use OpenID in the past, but moved to Facebook Connect.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Blogger also used OpenID, but since May 2018 no longer supports it.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] OpenID is a decentralized authentication protocol that allows users to authenticate with multiple websites using a single set of credentials, eliminating the need for separate usernames and passwords for each website.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] OpenID authenticates a user with an identity provider (IdP), who then provides the user with a unique identifier (called an OpenID).
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] This identifier can then be used to authenticate the user with any website that supports OpenID.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] When a user visits a website that supports OpenID authentication, the website will redirect the user to their chosen IdP.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The IdP will then prompt the user to authenticate themselves (e.g., by entering a username and password).
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Once the user is authenticated, the IdP will generate an OpenID and send it back to the website.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The website can then use this OpenID to authenticate the user without needing to know their actual credentials.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] OpenID is built on top of several existing standards, including HTTP, HTML, and XML.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] OpenID relies on a number of technologies, including a discovery mechanism that allows websites to find the IdP associated with a particular OpenID, as well as security mechanisms to protect against phishing and other attacks.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] One of the key benefits of OpenID is that it allows users to control their own identity information, rather than relying on individual websites to store and manage their login credentials.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] This can be particularly important in cases where websites are vulnerable to security breaches or where users are concerned about the privacy of their personal information.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] OpenID has been widely adopted by a number of large websites and service providers, including Google, Yahoo!, and PayPal.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The protocol is also used by a number of open source projects and frameworks, including Ruby on Rails and Django.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The end user interacts with a relying party (such as a website) that provides an option to specify an OpenID for the purposes of authentication; an end user typically has previously registered an OpenID (e.g.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] `alice.openid.example.org`) with an OpenID provider (e.g.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The relying party typically transforms the OpenID into a canonical URL form (e.g.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The `checkid_immediate` mode can fall back to the `checkid_setup` mode if the operation cannot be automated.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] First, the relying party and the OpenID provider (optionally) establish a shared secret, referenced by an *associate handle*, which the relying party then stores.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] If using the `checkid_setup` mode, the relying party redirects the end user's user-agent to the OpenID provider so the end user can authenticate directly with the OpenID provider.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The method of authentication may vary, but typically, an OpenID provider prompts the end user for a password or some cryptographic token, and then asks whether the end user trusts the relying party to receive the necessary identity details.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] If the end user declines the OpenID provider's request to trust the relying party, then the user-agent is redirected back to the relying party with a message indicating that authentication was rejected; the relying party in turn refuses to authenticate the end user.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] If the end user accepts the OpenID provider's request to trust the relying party, then the user-agent is redirected back to the relying party along with the end user's credentials.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] That relying party must then confirm that the credentials really came from the OpenID provider.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] In contrast, a *stateless* or *dumb* relying party must make one more background request (`check_authentication`) to ensure that the data indeed came from the OpenID provider.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] After the OpenID has been verified, authentication is considered successful and the end user is considered logged into the relying party under the identity specified by the given OpenID (e.g.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The relying party typically then stores the end user's OpenID along with the end user's other session information.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] To obtain an OpenID-enabled URL that can be used to log into OpenID-enabled websites, a user registers an OpenID identifier with an identity provider.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Identity providers offer the ability to register a URL (typically a third-level domain, e.g. username.example.com) that will automatically be configured with OpenID authentication service.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Once they have registered an OpenID, a user can also use an existing URL under their own control (such as a blog or home page) as an alias or "delegated identity".
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] They simply insert the appropriate OpenID tags in the HTML or serve a Yadis document.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Starting with OpenID Authentication 2.0 (and some 1.1 implementations), there are two types of identifiers that can be used with OpenID: URLs and XRIs.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] XRIs are a new form of Internet identifier designed specifically for cross-domain digital identity.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] For example, XRIs come in two forms—i-names and i-numbers—that are usually registered simultaneously as synonyms.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] I-names are reassignable (like domain names), while i-numbers are never reassigned.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] When an XRI i-name is used as an OpenID identifier, it is immediately resolved to the synonymous i-number (the CanonicalID element of the XRDS document).
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] This i-number is the OpenID identifier stored by the relying party.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] In this way, both the user and the relying party are protected from the end user's OpenID identity ever being taken over by another party as can happen with a URL based on a reassignable DNS name.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The OpenID Foundation (OIDF) promotes and enhances the OpenID community and technologies.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The OIDF is a non-profit international standards development organization of individual developers, government agencies and companies who wish to promote and protect OpenID.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The OpenID Foundation was formed in June 2007 and serves as a public trust organization representing an open community of developers, vendors and users.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] OIDF assists the community by providing needed infrastructure and help in promoting and supporting adoption of OpenID.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] This includes managing intellectual property and trade marks as well a fostering viral growth and global participation in OpenID.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] OIDF is a global organization to promote digital identity and to encourage the further adoption of OpenID, the OIDF has encouraged the creation of member chapters.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Member chapters are officially part of the Foundation and work within their own constituency to support the development and adoption of OpenID as a framework for user-centric identity on the internet.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The OIDF ensures that OpenID specifications are freely implementable therefore the OIDF requires all contributors to sign a contribution agreement.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] This agreement both grants a copyright license to the Foundation to publish the collective specifications and includes a patent non-assertion agreement.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The non-assertion agreement states that the contributor will not sue someone for implementing OpenID specifications.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The OpenID trademark in the United States was assigned to the OpenID Foundation in March 2008.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] It had been registered by NetMesh Inc. before the OpenID Foundation was operational.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] In Europe, as of August 31, 2007, the OpenID trademark is registered to the OpenID Europe Foundation.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The OpenID logo was designed by Randy "ydnar" Reddig, who in 2005 had expressed plans to transfer the rights to an OpenID organization.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Sun Microsystems, VeriSign and a number of smaller companies involved in OpenID have issued patent non-assertion covenants covering OpenID 1.1 specifications.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The covenants state that the companies will not assert any of their patents against OpenID implementations and will revoke their promises from anyone who threatens, or asserts, patents against OpenID implementors.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] In March, 2012, a research paper reported two generic security issues in OpenID.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Both issues allow an attacker to sign in to a victim's relying party accounts.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] For the first issue, OpenID and Google (an Identity Provider of OpenID) both published security advisories to address it.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Google's advisory says "An attacker could forge an OpenID request that doesn't ask for the user's email address, and then insert an unsigned email address into the IdPs response.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] If the attacker relays this response to a website that doesn't notice that this attribute is unsigned, the website may be tricked into logging the attacker in to any local account." The research paper claims that many popular websites have been confirmed vulnerable, including Yahoo!
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Mail, smartsheet.com, Zoho, manymoon.com, diigo.com.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The researchers have notified the affected parties, who have then fixed their vulnerable code.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] For the second issue, the paper called it "Data Type Confusion Logic Flaw", which also allows attackers to sign in to victims' RP accounts.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Google and PayPal were initially confirmed vulnerable.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] OpenID published a vulnerability report on the flaw.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The report says Google and PayPal have applied fixes, and suggest other OpenID vendors to check their implementations.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Some observers have suggested that OpenID has security weaknesses and may prove vulnerable to phishing attacks.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] For example, a malicious relaying party may forward the end user to a bogus identity provider authentication page asking that end user to input their credentials.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] On completion of this, the malicious party (who in this case also controls the bogus authentication page) could then have access to the end user's account with the identity provider, and then use that end user's OpenID to log into other services.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] In an attempt to combat possible phishing attacks, some OpenID providers mandate that the end user needs to be authenticated with them prior to an attempt to authenticate with the relying party.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] This relies on the end user knowing the policy of the identity provider.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Other security issues identified with OpenID involve lack of privacy and failure to address the trust problem.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] However, this problem is not unique to OpenID and is simply the state of the Internet as commonly used.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The Identity Provider does, however, get a log of your OpenID logins; they know when you logged into what website, making cross-site tracking much easier.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] A compromised OpenID account is also likely to be a more serious breach of privacy than a compromised account on a single site.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Another important vulnerability is present in the last step in the authentication scheme when TLS/SSL are not used: the redirect-URL from the identity provider to the relying party.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The problem with this redirect is the fact that anyone who can obtain this URL (e.g. by sniffing the wire) can replay it and get logged into the site as the victim user.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Some of the identity providers use nonces (a number used just once) to allow a user to log into the site once and fail all the consecutive attempts.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The nonce solution works if the user is the first one to use the URL.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] However, a fast attacker who is sniffing the wire can obtain the URL and immediately reset a user's TCP connection (as an attacker is sniffing the wire and knows the required TCP sequence numbers) and then execute the replay attack as described above.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Thus nonces only protect against passive attackers, but cannot prevent active attackers from executing the replay attack.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Use of TLS/SSL in the authentication process can significantly reduce this risk.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] On May 1, 2014, a bug dubbed "Covert Redirect related to OAuth 2.0 and OpenID" was disclosed.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] It was discovered by mathematics doctoral student Wang Jing at the School of Physical and Mathematical Sciences, Nanyang Technological University, Singapore.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The announcement of OpenID is: "'Covert Redirect', publicized in May 2014, is an instance of attackers using open redirectors – a well-known threat, with well-known means of prevention.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] "The general consensus, so far, is that Covert Redirect is not as bad, but still a threat.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] A patch was not immediately made available.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Ori Eisen, founder, chairman and chief innovation officer at 41st Parameter told Sue Marquette Poremba, "In any distributed system, we are counting of the good nature of the participants to do the right thing.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] In cases like OAuth and OpenID, the distribution is so vast that it is unreasonable to expect each and every website to patch up in the near future".
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The original OpenID authentication protocol was developed in May 2005 by Brad Fitzpatrick, creator of popular community website LiveJournal, while working at Six Apart.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Initially referred to as Yadis (an acronym for "Yet another distributed identity system"), it was named OpenID after the openid.net domain name was given to Six Apart to use for the project.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] OpenID support was soon implemented on LiveJournal and fellow LiveJournal engine community DeadJournal for blog post comments and quickly gained attention in the digital identity community.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Web developer JanRain was an early supporter of OpenID, providing OpenID software libraries and expanding its business around OpenID-based services.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] In late June, discussions started between OpenID users and developers from enterprise software company NetMesh, leading to collaboration on interoperability between OpenID and NetMesh's similar Light-weight Identity (LID) protocol.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The direct result of the collaboration was the Yadis discovery protocol, adopting the name originally used for OpenID.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The new Yadis was announced on October 24, 2005.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] After a discussion at the 2005 Internet Identity Workshop a few days later, XRI/i-names developers joined the Yadis project, contributing their Extensible Resource Descriptor Sequence (XRDS) format for utilization in the protocol.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] In December, developers at Sxip Identity began discussions with the OpenID/Yadis community after announcing a shift in the development of version 2.0 of its Simple Extensible Identity Protocol (SXIP) to URL-based identities like LID and OpenID.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] In March 2006, JanRain developed a Simple Registration (SREG) extension for OpenID enabling primitive profile-exchange and in April submitted a proposal to formalize extensions to OpenID.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The same month, work had also begun on incorporating full XRI support into OpenID.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Around early May, key OpenID developer David Recordon left Six Apart, joining VeriSign to focus more on digital identity and guidance for the OpenID spec.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] By early June, the major differences between the SXIP 2.0 and OpenID projects were resolved with the agreement to support multiple personas in OpenID by submission of an identity provider URL rather than a full identity URL.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Late in 2006, a ZDNet opinion piece made the case for OpenID to users, web site operators and entrepreneurs.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] On January 31, 2007, Symantec announced support for OpenID in its Identity Initiative products and services.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] A week later, on February 6 Microsoft made a joint announcement with JanRain, Sxip, and VeriSign to collaborate on interoperability between OpenID and Microsoft's Windows CardSpace digital identity platform, with particular focus on developing a phishing-resistant authentication solution for OpenID.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] As part of the collaboration, Microsoft pledged to support OpenID in its future identity server products and JanRain, Sxip, and VeriSign pledged to add support for Microsoft's Information Card profile to their future identity solutions.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] In mid-February, AOL announced that an experimental OpenID provider service was functional for all AOL and AOL Instant Messenger (AIM) accounts.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] In May, Sun Microsystems began working with the OpenID community, announcing an OpenID program, as well as entering a non-assertion covenant with the OpenID community, pledging not to assert any of its patents against implementations of OpenID.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] In June, OpenID leadership formed the OpenID Foundation, an Oregon-based public benefit corporation for managing the OpenID brand and property.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The same month, an independent OpenID Europe Foundation was formed in Belgium by Snorri Giorgetti.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] By early December, non-assertion agreements were collected by the major contributors to the protocol and the final OpenID Authentication 2.0 and OpenID Attribute Exchange 1.0 specifications were ratified on December 5.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] In mid-January 2008, Yahoo! announced initial OpenID 2.0 support, both as a provider and as a relying party, releasing the provider service by the end of the month.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] In early February, Google, IBM, Microsoft, VeriSign and Yahoo! joined the OpenID Foundation as corporate board members.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Around early May, SourceForge, Inc. introduced OpenID provider and relying party support to leading open source software development website SourceForge.net.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] In late July, popular social network service MySpace announced support for OpenID as a provider.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] In late October, Google launched support as an OpenID provider and Microsoft announced that Windows Live ID would support OpenID.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] In November, JanRain announced a free hosted service, RPX Basic, that allows websites to begin accepting OpenIDs for registration and login without having to install, integrate and configure the OpenID open source libraries.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] In January 2009, PayPal joined the OpenID Foundation as a corporate member, followed shortly by Facebook in February.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The OpenID Foundation formed an executive committee and appointed Don Thibeau as executive director.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] In March, MySpace launched their previously announced OpenID provider service, enabling all MySpace users to use their MySpace URL as an OpenID.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] In May, Facebook launched their relying party functionality, letting users use an automatic login-enabled OpenID account (e.g.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] In September 2013, Janrain announced that MyOpenID.com would be shut down on February 1, 2014; a pie chart showed Facebook and Google dominate the social login space as of Q2 2013.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Facebook has since left OpenID; it is no longer a sponsor, represented on the board, or permitting OpenID logins.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] In May 2016, Symantec announced that they would be discontinuing their pip.verisignlabs.com OpenID personal identity portal service.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] In March 2018, Stack Overflow announced an end to OpenID support, citing insufficient usage to justify the cost.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] In the announcement, it was stated that based on activity, users strongly preferred Facebook, Google, and e-mail/password based account authentication.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] OpenID is a way to use a single set of user credentials to access multiple sites, while OAuth facilitates the authorization of one site to access and use information related to the user's account on another site.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Although OAuth is not an authentication protocol, it can be used as part of one.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The following drawing highlights the differences between using OpenID versus OAuth for authentication.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Note that with OpenID, the process starts with the application asking the user for their identity (typically an OpenID URI), whereas in the case of OAuth, the application directly requests a limited access OAuth Token (valet key) to access the APIs (enter the house) on user's behalf.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] If the user can grant that access, the application can retrieve the unique identifier for establishing the profile (identity) using the APIs.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] OpenID provides a cryptographic verification mechanism that prevents the attack below against users who misuse OAuth for authentication.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Note that the valet key does not describe the user in any way, it only provides limited access rights, to some house (which is not even necessarily the user's, they just had a key).
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Therefore if the key becomes compromised (the user is malicious and managed to steal the key to someone else's house), then the user can impersonate the house owner to the application who requested their authenticity.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] If the key is compromised by any point in the chain of trust, a malicious user may intercept it and use it to impersonate user X for any application relying on OAuth2 for pseudo authentication against the same OAuth authorization server.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Conversely, the notarized letter contains the user's signature, which can be checked by the requesting application against the user, so this attack is not viable.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The letter can use public-key cryptography to be authenticated.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] Published in February 2014 by the OpenID Foundation, OpenID Connect (OIDC) is the third generation of OpenID technology.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] It is an authentication layer on top of the OAuth 2.0 authorization framework.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] It allows computing clients to verify the identity of an end user based on the authentication performed by an authorization server, as well as to obtain the basic profile information about the end user in an interoperable and REST-like manner.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] In technical terms, OpenID Connect specifies a RESTful HTTP API, using JSON as a data format.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] OpenID Connect allows a range of parties, including web-based, mobile and JavaScript clients, to request and receive information about authenticated sessions and end users.
[src:openid-connect/openid-connect] The OpenID Connect specification is extensible, supporting optional features such as encryption of identity data, discovery of OpenID providers, and session management.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] True single sign-on allows the user to log in once and access services without re-entering authentication factors.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] It should not be confused with same-sign on (Directory Server Authentication), often accomplished by using the Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) and stored LDAP databases on (directory) servers.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] A simple version of single sign-on can be achieved over IP networks using cookies but only if the sites share a common DNS parent domain.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] Conversely, **single sign-off** or **single log-out** (**SLO**) is the property whereby a single action of signing out terminates access to multiple software systems.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] As different applications and resources support different authentication mechanisms, single sign-on must internally store the credentials used for initial authentication and translate them to the credentials required for the different mechanisms.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] Other shared authentication schemes, such as OpenID and OpenID Connect, offer other services that may require users to make choices during a sign-on to a resource, but can be configured for single sign-on if those other services (such as user consent) are disabled.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] An increasing number of federated social logons, like Facebook Connect, do require the user to enter consent choices upon first registration with a new resource, and so are not always single sign-on in the strictest sense.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] SSO shares centralized authentication servers that all other applications and systems use for authentication purposes and combines this with techniques to ensure that users do not have to actively enter their credentials more than once.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] The term *reduced sign-on* (RSO) has been used by some to reflect the fact that *single sign-on* is impractical in addressing the need for different levels of secure access in the enterprise, and as such more than one authentication server may be necessary.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] As single sign-on provides access to many resources once the user is initially authenticated ("keys to the castle"), it increases the negative impact in case the credentials are available to other people and misused.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] Therefore, single sign-on requires an increased focus on the protection of the user credentials, and should ideally be combined with strong authentication methods like smart cards and one-time password tokens.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] Single sign-on also increases dependence on highly-available authentication systems; a loss of their availability can result in denial of access to all systems unified under the SSO.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] SSO can be configured with session failover capabilities in order to maintain the system operation.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] Nonetheless, the risk of system failure may make single sign-on undesirable for systems to which access must be guaranteed at all times, such as security or plant-floor systems.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] Furthermore, the use of single-sign-on techniques utilizing social networking services such as Facebook may render third party websites unusable within libraries, schools, or workplaces that block social media sites for productivity reasons.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] It can also cause difficulties in countries with active censorship regimes, such as China and its "Golden Shield Project", where the third party website may not be actively censored, but is effectively blocked if a user's social login is blocked.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] In March 2012, a research paper reported an extensive study on the security of social login mechanisms.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] The authors found 8 serious logic flaws in high-profile ID providers and relying party websites, such as OpenID (including Google ID and PayPal Access), Facebook, Janrain, Freelancer, FarmVille, and Sears.com.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] Because the researchers informed ID providers and relying party websites prior to public announcement of the discovery of the flaws, the vulnerabilities were corrected, and no security breaches have been reported.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] In May 2014, a vulnerability named Covert Redirect was disclosed.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] It was first reported "Covert Redirect Vulnerability Related to OAuth 2.0 and OpenID" by its discoverer Wang Jing, a Mathematical PhD student from Nanyang Technological University, Singapore.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] In fact, almost all Single sign-on protocols are affected.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] Covert Redirect takes advantage of third-party clients susceptible to cross-site scripting (XSS) or open redirect.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] In December 2020, flaws in federated authentication systems were discovered to have been utilized by attackers during the 2020 United States federal government data breach.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] Another security issue is that if the session used for SSO is stolen (which can be protected with the HttpOnly cookie flag unlike the SSO token), the attacker can access all the websites that are using the SSO system.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] As originally implemented in Kerberos and SAML, single sign-on did not give users any choices about releasing their personal information to each new resource that the user visited.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] This worked well enough within a single enterprise, like MIT where Kerberos was invented, or major corporations where all of the resources were internal sites.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] However, as federated services like Active Directory Federation Services proliferated, the user's private information was sent out to affiliated sites not under control of the enterprise that collected the data from the user.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] Since privacy regulations are now tightening with legislation like the GDPR, the newer methods like OpenID Connect have started to become more attractive; for example MIT, the originator of Kerberos, now supports OpenID Connect.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] Single sign-on in theory can work without revealing identifying information such as email addresses to the relying party (credential consumer), but many credential providers do not allow users to configure what information is passed on to the credential consumer.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] As of 2019, Google and Facebook sign-in do not require users to share email addresses with the credential consumer.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] "Sign in with Apple" introduced in iOS 13 allows a user to request a unique relay email address each time the user signs up for a new service, thus reducing the likelihood of account linking by the credential consumer.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] Windows environment - Windows login fetches TGT.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] Active Directory-aware applications fetch service tickets, so the user is not prompted to re-authenticate.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] Unix/Linux environment - Login via Kerberos PAM modules fetches TGT.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] Kerberized client applications such as Evolution, Firefox, and SVN use service tickets, so the user is not prompted to re-authenticate.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] Mobile environment - Apple added native Kerberos support in IOS 13.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] On Android a Mobile Device Management service can add support for Kerberos.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] Initial sign-on prompts the user for the smart card.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] Additional software applications also use the smart card, without prompting the user to re-enter credentials.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] Smart-card-based single sign-on can either use certificates or passwords stored on the smart card.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) is an XML-based method for exchanging user security information between an SAML identity provider and a SAML service provider.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] SAML 2.0 supports W3C XML encryption and service-provider–initiated web browser single sign-on exchanges.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] A user wielding a user agent (usually a web browser) is called the subject in SAML-based single sign-on.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] The user requests a web resource protected by a SAML service provider.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] The service provider, wishing to know the identity of the user, issues an authentication request to a SAML identity provider through the user agent.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] The identity provider is the one that provides the user credentials.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] The service provider trusts the user information from the identity provider to provide access to its services or resources.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] A newer variation of single-sign-on authentication has been developed using mobile devices as access credentials.
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] A mobile device is "something you have", as opposed to a password which is "something you know", or biometrics (fingerprint, retinal scan, facial recognition, etc.) which is "something you are".
[src:openid-connect/single-sign-on] Security experts recommend using at least two out of these three factors (multi-factor authentication) for best protection.
